<HEADLINE>
<P>
OUT AND ABOUT / C.C. BROWN'S: SUNDAE SCHOOL 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By CHRISTINA V. GODBEY 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 C.C. Brown's ice cream parlor has had its share of licks over the years. 
</P>
<P>
 Despite recessions, wars and competition from national chain shops, the 
legendary ice cream parlor has managed not to melt away from its historic home 
on Hollywood Boulevard. 
</P>
<P>
 The parlor was founded in 1906 by Clarence Clifton Brown, an Ohio-born candy 
maker who brought his trade and tools to Southern California in a covered 
wagon. He originally set up shop at 7th and Hill streets in Downtown Los 
Angeles. The parlor moved to its current location in 1928, complete with its 
original booths and metal serving dishes, which keep the ice cream cold. 
</P>
<P>
 Brown distinguished himself among competitors by concocting toppings that 
tasted more like candy than syrup. 
</P>
<P>
 In 1946, chemist John Schumacher started buying into C.C. Brown's, acquiring 
it from Brown's son, Cliff, in 1963. Schumacher continued to run the business 
just as generations remembered it, until his death earlier this year. Today, 
the parlor is still family-owned and operated by his wife, Jo Ellen, and their 
children, Heidi, Heather and Tim. 
</P>
<P>
 "It's an old-fashioned ice cream parlor where everything is homemade," said Jo 
Ellen Schumacher. "We have really tried to preserve things the way Mr. Brown 
would have wanted." 
</P>
<P>
 The shop has served as a set for a number of films and television programs 
such as "Highway to Heaven." It has also made its way into David Hoffman's 
guidebook, "The Joy of Pigging Out," which includes only 24 ice cream vendors. 
</P>
<P>
 C.C. Brown's offers more than seven dozen types of sundaes. The menu offers 
vanilla, mocha, chocolate and strawberry ice cream as well as lemon sherbet. 
Three hot toppings, fudge, caramel and golden mocha, are available. Sundaes 
range from $4.95 to $5.75, depending on the selection. 
</P>
<P>
 Ice cream is also available by the scoop for $1.25 (small) and $1.75 (large). 
</P>
<P>
 C.C. Brown's ice cream parlor, 7007 Hollywood Blvd., Hollywood. Hours are from 
1 to 10:30 p.m. Monday through Thursday and 1 p.m. to midnight Friday and 
Saturday. Closed Sundays. Information: (213) 464-9726. CHRISTINA V. GODBEY 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column; Restaurant Review 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
