<HEADLINE>
<P>
WEST VALLEY FOCUS: WOODLAND HILLS; COLLEGE AIMS TO LURE WORKERS TO CLASS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By SUSAN BYRNES 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 In an effort to entice Valley employees back to the books, directors of the 
adult education program at Pierce College are mailing hundreds of flyers to 
local businesses and sponsoring orientation sessions at workplaces throughout 
the San Fernando Valley. 
</P>
<P>
 The 400-student Project for Adult College Education, PACE, which was 
established on the Pierce campus in 1986, offers working adults a chance to 
earn an associate in arts degree in five semesters of evening and weekend 
classes. 
</P>
<P>
 Directors of the program say the sluggish economy of the past few years has 
emphasized the need for workers to boost their education. 
</P>
<P>
 "Four years ago, it was for career advancement that most people were coming," 
PACE Director Jeff Cooper said. "More and more they are coming for job 
security." 
</P>
<P>
 The program, which allows working adults to finish a degree program four times 
faster than through traditional night school classes, costs about $400 for a 
semester. 
</P>
<P>
 Many students who graduate from PACE go on to earn a bachelor's degree at a 
four-year college or university. For more information, call (818) 719-6455. 
SUSAN BYRNES 
</P>
</TEXT>
